 for bestpractices and # Run Details Page Prompt

Overview:
You are building a feature-rich Run Details Page for LifeOps, the multi-agent AI operating system. This page surfaces a single cron/agent run in depth, including inputs, agent-to-agent message trace, logs, diffs, artifacts, timing, and outcome, with the ability to revert actions when permitted. The page must integrate with the Audit Trail & Reversibility, Conflict Resolution Engine, Cronjobs Engine, Agent Orchestration & Messaging, Scoped Memory Store, Approvals Queue, Cronjob Editor, and Agent Trace & Debugger. Emphasize determinism, explainability, traceability, security, and robust runtime safety (null guards, proper typing, and array handling as specified).

Page purpose and goals:
- Provide a comprehensive, auditable view of a single run.
- Show the full lifecycle: inputs, negotiation/trace, decisions, actions taken, artifacts produced, timing data, and outcomes.
- Enable controlled reversibility with validators and clear warnings.
- Enable investigators, operators, and auditors to understand why decisions were made (explainability) and how to revert when allowed.
- Tie into related features to present a holistic picture: audit trail, conflict resolution rationale, run history, and artifacts.

Page Description (Full Detail):
- This Run Details Page is a read/inspect and action surface for a specific cron/agent run. It should render:
  - Header
    - Run ID (read-only, globally unique)
    - Cronjob name or workflow name
    - Start timestamp, end timestamp, duration
    - Run status (e.g., queued, running, succeeded, failed, aborted)
    - Quick actions: Revert, Re-run (where allowed), export artifacts
  - Inputs & Context
    - Original input payload template with bound variables
    - Effective input payload used for this run
    - Scope and permissions that applied
  - Agent-to-Agent Message Trace
    - Timeline / sequence of messages between agents
    - For each message: sender, receiver, timestamp, message type, payload excerpt, outcome
    - Handoffs, negotiations, alerts, consensus events
  - Logs & Events
    - Structured logs with levels, timestamps, components
    - Errors, warnings, informational events
    - Filter/search capabilities (level, source, time range)
  - Diffs
    - Before/after diffs for resources modified during the run
    - Metadata about what changed, who approved, and why
  - Artifacts
    - Generated files, outputs, bundles
    - Download links with provenance (which run, which agent, when)
  - Timing & Performance
    - Per-step timing breakdown (agent processing, messaging latency, I/O, retries)
    - Deadlines, backoffs, retries, and timeouts
  - Outcome & Reversibility
    - Final outcome, rationale, and explicit reversible actions with validators
    - If reversible, show Revert action button with required confirmations and constraints
  - Audit Trails
    - Immutable, append-only trail of this run, approvals, user actions
    - Revert validators: what conditions must be met to reverse; who approved; when
  - Related Context
    - Reference to related runs (preceding/following), approvals state, and linked cronjob object
- Connected UI components must visually align with the project’s design system and color/typography guidelines described below.

Components to Build (each with technical details)
1) RunDetailsHeader
- Displays Run ID, Cronjob/Workflow name, status badge, start/end times, duration, and primary action buttons (Revert, Re-run, Export).
- Behavior:
  - Status badge uses color semantics: success, warning, danger, in-progress.
  - Revert button enabled only if the run is reversible and validators pass.
- Accessibility: aria-labels for screen readers; keyboard accessible.

2) InputsPanel
- Shows Inputs & Context: bound inputs, effective inputs, scope, and permissions.
- UI: collapsible section; show JSON pretty view with syntax highlighting; include copy-to-clipboard.
- Guard rails: if inputs are undefined, render empty state with guidance.

3) MessageTraceViewer
- Timeline view for agent-to-agent messages.
- For each event: time, sender, receiver, type, summary, payload excerpt.
- Visual: horizontal lanes per agent, vertical timeline; clickable events expand to show payload details.
- Features: search, filter by sender/receiver/type, collapse long chains.
- Data handling: data ?? [] for arrays; Array.isArray guards around mapping.

4) LogsEventsPanel
- Structured logs with levels; filter by level, source, time range.
- Display: table/list with expandable rows for stack traces or details.
- Performance: virtualized list if large data; pagination or infinite scroll as needed.

5) DiffsViewer
- Show resource diffs with Before/After views side-by-side or inline diffs.
- Support: filter by resource type, show change rationale, author, and revert risk level.
- Guard: gracefully handle missing diff chunks; use [] fallback.

6) ArtifactsPanel
- List of artifacts with metadata: name, type, size, produced at, downloadable link, provenance.
- Actions: download, view, verify integrity (checksum), copy link.

7) TimingPane
- Per-step timing, latency metrics, backoffs, retries.
- Visualization: small charts or sparkline per step; tooltip with exact ms values.

8) ReversibilityPanel
- Displays reversible actions and their validators; shows required confirmations and user roles.
- Buttons: Confirm Revert, Cancel; show revert rationale and audit trail entry preview.
- Validation: ensure user has permission and that run meets revert criteria.

9) AuditTrailPanel
- Immutable, append-only log view for this run and related actions.
- Filters, export to CSV/JSON.

10) RelatedContextPanel
- Links to antecedent/successor runs, cronjob object details, approval state.

11) ApprovalsQueueLink (integration point)
- Quick navigation to the Approvals Queue item related to this run if applicable; show status snapshot.

12) CronjobEditorLink (integration point)
- Quick navigation to the Cronjob Editor for the associated cronjob.

13) AgentTraceDebuggerLink
- Quick navigation to Agent Trace & Debugger tool for deeper inspection.

Implementation Requirements

Frontend
- Framework: React (with TypeScript) or a framework used within LifeOps consistent with other modules.
- State management: useState/useEffect; consider lightweight context or store for run details; avoid global state leaks.
- Data fetching: placeholder API layer; ensure all calls guard against null/undefined.
- Runtime safety rules applied to all components:
  - Use data ?? [] when consuming arrays from API results.
  - Guard array methods with (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
  - Initialize useState with proper types, e.g., useState<RunArtifact[]>([]) for arrays.
  - Validate API responses: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Optional chaining everywhere for nested API data.
  - Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}.
- UI components:
  - Card-based layout with the described design system.
  - Responsive behavior for wide and narrow viewports.
  - Accessible color contrast per design, support for dark mode if applicable.
- Interactions:
  - Sorting, filtering, pagination for long traces/logs.
  - Expandable rows, tooltips, keyboard accessible controls.
  - Animations: subtle lift on hover, smooth transitions for panel toggles.
- Revert flow:
  - Revert button triggers a reversible action pathway with a validator step. Display required confirmations and validators in UI.
  - If not allowed, explain why and disable the control with tooltip.

Backend
- API endpoints (mock or actual, aligning with existing APIs in LifeOps):
  - GET /runs/:runId
    - Returns RunDetail including: id, cronjobId, cronjobName, startedAt, endedAt, status, inputs, effectiveInputs, trace, logs, diffs, artifacts, timing, outcome, reversibleActions, auditTrail
  - GET /runs/:runId/logs
  - GET /runs/:runId/trace
  - GET /runs/:runId/diffs
  - GET /runs/:runId/artifacts
  - POST /runs/:runId/revert
    - Payload: { reason, validatorId, confirmations }
  - GET /cronjobs/:cronjobId
  - GET /approvals/:approvalId (for context)
- Data models (TypeScript interfaces / GraphQL/REST types as appropriate)
  - RunDetail
    - id: string
    - cronjobId: string
    - cronjobName: string
    - startedAt: string
    - endedAt: string
    - durationMs?: number
    - status: 'queued'|'running'|'succeeded'|'failed'|'aborted'
    - inputs: any
    - effectiveInputs: any
    - trace: TraceEvent[]
    - logs: LogEvent[]
    - diffs: DiffChunk[]
    - artifacts: Artifact[]
    - timing: TimingSection[]
    - outcome: RunOutcome
    - reversibleActions: ReversibleAction[]
    - auditTrail: AuditEvent[]
  - TraceEvent
    - id, timestamp, sender, receiver, type, payloadExcerpt, fullPayload?
  - LogEvent
    - timestamp, level, source, message, metadata
  - DiffChunk
    - resourceId, before, after, changedFields, author, reason
  - Artifact
    - id, name, type, size, producedAt, url, checksum
  - TimingSection
    - name, durationMs, details
  - RunOutcome
    - success: boolean, summary, details
  - ReversibleAction
    - actionId, type, targetResource, requiredValidators, status
  - AuditEvent
    - id, timestamp, userId, action, details

Integration
- Data flow:
  - Run Details page fetches RunDetail via GET /runs/:runId
  - Uses nested resources (trace, logs, artifacts, diffs) as separate endpoints or embedded payloads; ensure consistent fetching strategy with fallbacks data ?? [].
  - Revert action POST to /runs/:runId/revert with necessary confirmations and validator info.
  - The Run Details page should surface and link to:
    - Approvals Queue item for this run (if applicable)
    - Cronjob Editor for the associated cronjob
    - Agent Trace & Debugger tool for deeper analysis
- State consistency:
  - Cache minimal metadata client-side; rely on API for live data
  - Use optimistic UI only for non-destructive actions with clear rollbacks on error

User Experience Flow
- Step 1: User navigates to Run Details page for a specific run from the Master Cronjobs dashboard or Approvals Queue.
- Step 2: Page loads RunDetail data and renders header with status, duration, and actions.
- Step 3: User reviews Inputs & Context; expand as needed to see bound variables and scope.
- Step 4: User inspects Message Trace Viewer for an end-to-end agent communication timeline; can filter and search.
- Step 5: User views Logs & Events for diagnostic context; filters available.
- Step 6: User examines Diffs to understand what resources changed; review rationale.
- Step 7: User opens Artifacts to access generated outputs; downloads as needed.
- Step 8: User reviews Timing data to identify bottlenecks or retries.
- Step 9: If run is reversible, user proceeds to Reversibility panel to initiate revert; system validates and triggers validator checks; user confirms with required approvals.
- Step 10: User can navigate to related Cronjob Editor or Agent Trace & Debugger for deeper investigation.
- Step 11: Audit Trail is accessible for compliance and traceability.

Technical Specifications

Data Models
- Use TypeScript interfaces/types as defined above.
- Ensure all arrays are guarded: items = data ?? [], isArray checks when consuming data from API.

API Endpoints
- GET /runs/:runId -> RunDetail
- GET /runs/:runId/trace -> TraceEvent[]
- GET /runs/:runId/logs -> LogEvent[]
- GET /runs/:runId/diffs -> DiffChunk[]
- GET /runs/:runId/artifacts -> Artifact[]
- POST /runs/:runId/revert -> RevertResponse
- GET /cronjobs/:cronjobId -> CronJob
- GET /approvals/:approvalId -> Approval

